Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I'd say we should not set this as default. The parallel execution of our tests have broke so many times lately (I think it does not work more of the time than it does).

If you want to default this on your own environment, just make an alias for it.

Patch Set 2:

Just to add on the previous comment of mine. I'm fond of the idea having the parallel run of the tests, but rather not making it default until we have good track record it actually staying together while done so.

Patch Set 2:

Hi, Erno Kuvaja.
Actually we have problems with parallelism only in test_migrations, which I have fixed in the previous(dependent) patch. Also, we had had problems with test_swift_store, which recently was deleted(and for which I made a fix because I have not updated master at time).

Patch Set 2: -Code-Review

Hello Oleksii, thanks for working on this.

From the Jenkins result of nikhil's change [0] and my local testing result [1], I think there are three cases related to a race-condition issue, at least. According to now all test cases of store drivers have already been refactored and moved to glance_stroe tree/proj, so I think if this change could work well and verified by job/gate, then I'd love to see this change get merged due to adding concurrent testing to glance is a good way to go.

[0] http://logs.openstack.org/27/108427/1/check/gate-glance-python27/b67527d/testr_results.html.gz

[1] http://paste.openstack.org/show/91909/

Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

I've tested this change with a different concurrency and tests passed ok for me locally. Seems to be, that after test cases of store drivers were refactored, the only reason of race conditions were miration tests, which were refactored in the previous patch.

Patch Set 2:

Hi Oleksii,

That sounds great. As said, I'm personally all up for this as soon as we have seen a while the tests running parallel without breaking again. As this affects gate as well, I would not want to rush with this change, specially now under the release.

Thanks a million if you really got the issues there fixed. Lets see how stable the tests are for a while before merging this in? At least that's what I'd like to see.
